[In a separate BSE-L posting Holtz de Barr commented concerning compensation:
Date: Tue, 10 Feb 1998 08:05:19 +0000
From: Oz <Oz@upthorpe.demon.co.uk>
Source: Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy <BSE-L@RZ.UNI-KARLSRUHE.DE>

If you want to have a system you can believe in, then make it worthwhile
for a farmer to declare cases he is suspicious about, rather than send them
off early when unskilled people can't easily be sure of what it is. [He had
earlier commented on how very subtle the early signs of BSE can be.
Abandon the absurd whole herd culling policy, which is mere window
dressing, and institute over-generous compensation for new cases. I very
much doubt that any country actually wants to know how much BSE it really
has, however. A cynic might think that these regulations were drawn up for
exactly this purpose.
--
Oz
[There are many decades of MAFF experience in engendering farmer support,
positive and negative, and generous and rapid compensation is the most
efficient and the most economic. I have always been impressed with how
public spirited the great majority of UK farmers are, though of course
there are always some villains. During the '67-'68 FMD epidemic they
universally reported their suspicions fairly promptly even when it meant
their herd would be slaughtered almost within the hour. Out of the 2500
herds affected only a handful were delinquent. - Mod.MHJ
***
