Date: Mon, 9 Feb 1998 21:59:11 -0800
From: Tom Pringle, <tom@cyber-dyne.com>
Source: Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy <BSE-L@RZ.UNI-KARLSRUHE.DE>

The MAFF Web site is actually quite impressive though they have not gotten
around to, updating the chronology. They provide very interest summaries
of 75 completed and 60 ongoing research projects, without listing principal
investigator, at:
<http://www.maff.gov.uk/animalh/bse/bse-science/level-4-current-research.htm
l>
<http://www.maff.gov.uk/animalh/bse/bse-science/level-4-complted-research.ht
ml>
I wrote Louise Pinkey, the webmaster, l.pinkney@ahbse.maff.gov.uk, to see
how the reports can be obtained after they are completed, choosing (among
many interesting titles):
SE1803 Transmissibility of BSE to pigs by oral exposure to brain homogenate
[became SE1817 31/03/95
SE1804 Transmissibility of BSE to cattle by oronasal exposure to placentae
of affected cattle [became SE1818
These are to be completed by the end of March 98:
SE1801 BSE: Embryo transfer studies
SE1805 Transmissibility of BSE to domestic fowl by injection with brain
homogenate
These are a long way off:
SE1828 The exposure of British sheep and cattle to mites
SE1829 Replication of scrapie and BSE prions in mites
There are 8 graphs on BSE incidence at:
<http://www.maff.gov.uk/animalh/bse/index.html>
